nmental pollution, as well as a chronic national shortage of donors. In doing so, Wahlberg outlines the specific style of Chinese sperm banking that has emerged, shaped by the particular cultural, juridical, economic and social configurations that make up China’s restrictive reproductive complex. Good Quality shows how this high-throughput style shapes the ways in which men experience donation and how sperm is made available to couples who can afford it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aArtificial inseminationzChina. 0aSperm bankszChina. 0aSperm donorszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aazoospermic men.  achina.  achinese sperm banking.  achinese.  achronic national shortage.  achronic shortages.  acouples.  acultural.  adeclining sperm quality.  aeconomic.  aenvironmental pollution.  aexpensive.  aimpotent.  ajingzi weiji.  ajuridical.  apotential donors.  arestrictive reproduction.  asocial configurations.  asperm banks.  asperm crisis.  asperm donation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029777740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969995/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles